  "prompt": "Which keywords are associated with entry-level instructional design jobs?",
  "response": "Entry-level instructional design jobs often involve creating educational content, developing training materials, and collaborating with subject matter experts. Keywords associated with these roles can help job seekers identify relevant positions and tailor their resumes. Here are some common keywords:\n\n1. **Instructional Design**  \n2. **E-Learning**  \n3. **Learning Management System (LMS)**  \n4. **Curriculum Development**  \n5. **Training Materials**  \n6. **ADDIE Model** (Analysis, Design, Development, Implementation, Evaluation)  \n7. **Storyboarding**  \n8. **Multimedia Development**  \n9. **Educational Technology**  \n10. **Content Development**  \n11. **Assessment Design**  \n12. **Instructional Technology**  \n13. **Blended Learning**  \n14. **Online Learning**  \n15. **Course Design**  \n16. **Authoring Tools** (e.g., Articulate Storyline, Adobe Captivate, Camtasia)  \n17. **Instructional Strategies**  \n18. **Learner Engagement**  \n19. **Training Needs Analysis**  \n20. **SCORM Compliance**  \n21. **Gamification**  \n22. **Microlearning**  \n23. **User Experience (UX) Design**  \n24. **Collaboration Tools** (e.g., Trello, Slack, Microsoft Teams)  \n25. **Performance Support Tools**  \n26. **Instructional Writing**  \n27. **Visual Design**  \n28. **Project Management**  \n29. **Stakeholder Collaboration**  \n30. **Adaptive Learning**  \n\nThese keywords can be used in resumes, cover letters, and job search filters to align with the skills and responsibilities typically required for entry-level instructional design roles. Additionally, familiarity with these terms can help candidates better understand job descriptions and prepare for interviews.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
